docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:5:{"id":"nanogpt-speedrun","title":"modded-nanogpt: NanoGPT speedrun (GPT-2 124M-quality on FineWeb, 8xH100)","venue":"GitHub (KellerJordan/modded-nanogpt)","year":2026,"url":"https://github.com/KellerJordan/modded-nanogpt/tree/edf47a05a12062d661c4cfd4eef848c5ab5bed32","claim":"IMMUTABLE PROVENANCE PIN: repo commit edf47a05a12062d661c4cfd4eef848c5ab5bed32 (master HEAD of 2026-07-03; README re-fetched at that exact commit 2026-07-11). README at pinned commit documents 84 records since 2024-05-28; latest record #84 = 1.32 min (2026-05-21) to val loss <=3.28 on FineWeb vs the llm.c 45-min baseline (~34x wall-clock) on the leaderboard's fixed 8xH100 hardware/software configuration; records require enough run logs for p<0.01 statistical significance that mean val loss <=3.28. Techniques accumulated ACROSS records (bundled; per-component contributions unmeasured): Muon/NorMuon optimizer, rotary, QK-norm, ReLU^2, FlashAttention-3 long-short sliding windows, FP8/bf16 precision, multi-token prediction, value/bigram-hash embeddings. Wall-clock engineering record on one hardware config — NOT a training-FLOP comparison and NOT evidence a plain GPT-2 twin is 34x less compute-efficient.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:6:{"id":"muon-scalable-2025","title":"Muon is Scalable for LLM Training","venue":"arXiv","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.16982","claim":"With weight decay + per-parameter update-scale added, Muon achieves ~2x computational efficiency vs AdamW at compute-optimal training; scales to Moonlight 3B/16B-MoE on 5.7T tokens; distributed implementation + checkpoints released.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:10:{"id":"mobilellm-2024","title":"MobileLLM: Optimizing Sub-billion Parameter Language Models for On-Device Use Cases","venue":"ICML","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2402.14905","claim":"At 125M/350M, the COMBINED MobileLLM design package (deep-thin shape + embedding sharing + grouped-query attention) improves +2.7/+4.3 pp average accuracy over prior same-size models; block-wise weight sharing adds +0.7/+0.8. The pp figures are model-level package-vs-prior-models improvements, NOT single-factor causal estimates of deep-thin-vs-wide-shallow; the paper's internal design exploration supports deep-thin directionally within its own setting.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:11:{"id":"kaplan-2020","title":"Scaling Laws for Neural Language Models","venue":"arXiv","year":2020,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2001.08361","claim":"Loss is power-law in N, D, C with trends spanning >7 orders of magnitude; width/depth shape has minimal impact within tested ranges; recommends large models on modest data stopped before convergence (later corrected by Chinchilla/Porian).","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:12:{"id":"chinchilla-2022","title":"Training Compute-Optimal Large Language Models (Chinchilla)","venue":"arXiv (NeurIPS 2022 commonly credited; venue not restated on abs page this pass)","year":2022,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2203.15556","claim":"400+ models 70M-16B, 5-500B tokens: compute-optimal N and D scale equally (~20 tok/param); Chinchilla 70B (4x data) beats Gopher 280B at same compute, MMLU 67.5% (+7 over Gopher); isoFLOP profiles = approach 2.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:18:{"id":"gadre-2024","title":"Language models scale reliably with over-training and on downstream tasks","venue":"ICLR 2025 (proceedings.iclr.cc paper file surfaced this pass); arXiv 2024","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.08540","claim":"104-model testbed 0.011B-6.9B, 3 data distributions: scaling laws extrapolate across over-training amounts — predicted 1.4B/900B-token (32x overtrained) and 6.9B/138B runs from 300x-less-compute experiments; perplexity->downstream top-1-error power law at 20x less compute.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:21:{"id":"datadecide-2025","title":"DataDecide: How to Predict Best Pretraining Data with Small Experiments","venue":"ICML","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.11393","claim":"25 corpora x scales up to 1B params/100B tokens, 3 seeds, 30k checkpoints: ranking at a single small scale (150M) predicts best-at-1B in ~80% of comparisons (~20% flip at 8x scale); NONE of 8 scaling-law extrapolation baselines beat single-scale ranking; continuous likelihood metrics best proxies (>80% predictable at 0.01% of target compute). Domain: PRETRAINING-DATA selection between standard-architecture models at ~150M->1B — NOT symbolic-interface interventions, architecture changes, 5-30M models, or signed treatment-effect trends; transfers to the kot sweep protocol by analogy only.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:22:{"id":"bnsl-2022","title":"Broken Neural Scaling Laws","venue":"ICLR 2023","year":2022,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.14891","claim":"Smoothly-broken power laws model non-monotonic scaling (double descent, sharp inflections); seemingly smooth scaling curves may contain hidden breaks — extrapolating from few small-scale points carries inherent uncertainty.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:26:{"id":"toolformer-2023","title":"Toolformer: Language Models Can Teach Themselves to Use Tools","venue":"NeurIPS 2023 (openreview Yacmpz84TH surfaced this pass; abs page silent)","year":2023,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2302.04761","claim":"Self-supervised API-call learning (GPT-J 6.7B base). Scale sweep on GPT-2 family 124M/355M/775M/1.6B: 'the ability to leverage the provided tools only emerges at around 775M parameters; smaller models achieve similar performance both with and without tools' (exception: the easy Wikipedia-search API) — figure from paper body via PDF excerpt located this pass. Within-ONE-lineage observation in which scale co-varies with base capability, generated-call quality, filtering, and task mix: prior evidence of a POSSIBLE capacity threshold for learned interface use, not a general measured interface threshold.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:28:{"id":"phi-ctnl-satire-2023","title":"Pretraining on the Test Set Is All You Need","venue":"arXiv (explicit satire, 3 pages)","year":2023,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2309.08632","claim":"Satirical 1M-param 'phi-CTNL' achieves perfect benchmark scores by pretraining on the benchmarks: data-quality/emergence claims from curated corpora are uninterpretable without contamination audits.","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/TINY.sources.jsonl:31:{"id":"ruan-observational-2024","title":"Observational Scaling Laws and the Predictability of Language Model Performance","venue":"NeurIPS 2024 (spotlight)","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.10938","claim":"~100 public models define a low-dimensional capability space in which emergent phenomena, agent performance, and post-training technique value follow smooth predictable sigmoids. CARRIED from docs/next/lit/EVAL.md sect-5 (verified there 2026-07-11); UNVERIFIED-THIS-PASS.","verified":false}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:1:{"id":"minitron-2407.14679","title":"Compact Language Models via Pruning and Knowledge Distillation (Minitron)","venue":"arXiv (NVIDIA)","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.14679","claim":"Depth+width+head+MLP pruning with KD-based retraining on <3% of original data; 8B/4B derived from 15B need up to 40x fewer training tokens per model than from-scratch; 1.8x compute saving for the family; up to 16% MMLU improvement over from-scratch training under ISO-COMPUTE accounting, NOT equal tokens (re-verified 2026-07-11 at Sec 4.3/Table 11: 4B pruned+distilled on 100B KD tokens scores 37.81 MMLU vs 26.24 for the 150B-token from-scratch twin; scratch baseline gets more tokens because distillation pays teacher forward passes; asterisks mark iso-compute rows); Minitron comparable to Mistral-7B/Gemma-7B/Llama-3-8B","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:2:{"id":"minitron-practice-2408.11796","title":"LLM Pruning and Distillation in Practice: The Minitron Approach","venue":"arXiv (NVIDIA)","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2408.11796","claim":"Practice recipe: teacher correction (lightly fine-tune teacher on the distillation dataset when original pretraining data unavailable) before KD; evaluates depth pruning vs joint hidden/attention/MLP width pruning; Llama-3.1-8B->4B and Mistral-NeMo-12B->Minitron-8B (state-of-the-art at release), weights open","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:6:{"id":"deeper-layers-2403.17887","title":"The Unreasonable Ineffectiveness of the Deeper Layers","venue":"ICLR 2025","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2403.17887","claim":"Layer pruning selected by inter-layer representational (angular) similarity + QLoRA healing: minimal QA-benchmark degradation until up to ~half the layers of some open-weight models are removed; interpreted as under-utilisation of deep layers or shallow-layer-dominant knowledge storage","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:8:{"id":"distill-scaling-2502.08606","title":"Distillation Scaling Laws","venue":"ICML 2025 (Apple/Oxford)","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.08606","claim":"Distillation scaling law predicting student performance from compute split across teacher/student; distillation beats supervised pretraining only up to a compute level that scales predictably with student size and only when a teacher exists or many students amortise it; capacity gap (stronger teacher -> worse student) explained as learning-capacity gap; compute-optimal recipes given","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:10:{"id":"spinquant-2405.16406","title":"SpinQuant: LLM Quantization with Learned Rotations","venue":"ICLR 2025","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2405.16406","claim":"Identifies rotation parameterisations that leave full-precision output invariant; learns rotations (Stiefel-manifold optimisation) instead of random ones — random rotation choice alone swings downstream zero-shot reasoning by up to 13 points at 4-bit; strong W4A4KV4 results incl. LLaMA-3-8B. R1-R4 taxonomy (which merge into weights vs run online) NOT verified at source this session (HTML fetch 404) — carried from abstract only","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:11:{"id":"signed-perm-2606.31963","title":"Signed-Permutation Coordinate Transport for RMSNorm Transformers","venue":"arXiv","year":2026,"url":"https://arxiv.org/html/2606.31963","claim":"With generic per-channel RMSNorm gain the exact gauge (symmetry) group of the coordinate system is the signed-permutation group B_d = S_d x {+-1}^d, NOT O(d); LayerNorm charts have permutation gauge S_d UP TO A GLOBAL SIGN FLIP (re-verified 2026-07-11); permutation-only alignment is symmetry-incomplete for RMSNorm models (worked example: SAE reconstruction NMSE 0.004 -> 1.08 under permutation-only vs signed-permutation transport); steering vectors, SAEs, top-k neuron sets, attribution lists must be co-transported. WEIGHT: very recent single-author preprint scoped to coordinate transport of interpretability artifacts across checkpoints — strict-gauge statement to be independently re-derived in P3-D-DD, not the final word on transformer-surgery invariance","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:13:{"id":"lrh-2311.03658","title":"The Linear Representation Hypothesis and the Geometry of Large Language Models","venue":"ICML 2024 (also NeurIPS 2023 CRL workshop)","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2311.03658","claim":"Formalises linear representation of concepts; Euclidean inner product is the wrong geometry for concept directions — a 'causal inner product' (whitened basis) makes causally separable concepts orthogonal; validated on LLaMA-2; implies concept directions are generically NON-orthogonal in the naive residual-stream basis","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:15:{"id":"sae-canonical-2502.04878","title":"Sparse Autoencoders Do Not Find Canonical Units of Analysis","venue":"ICLR 2025 (per arXiv page)","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.04878","claim":"SAE stitching shows smaller SAEs are incomplete (larger SAEs contain novel latents, not just refinements); meta-SAEs decompose latents into interpretable parts ('Einstein' -> 'scientist'+'Germany'+'famous person'); conclusion: no canonical atomic feature set at any SAE size","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:16:{"id":"sae-seeds-2501.16615","title":"Sparse Autoencoders Trained on the Same Data Learn Different Features","venue":"arXiv (EleutherAI)","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2501.16615","claim":"131K-latent SAE on Llama-3-8B: only ~30% of features shared across random seeds; TopK SAEs more seed-dependent than ReLU+L1; consistent across layers/datasets/architectures — SAE decompositions are pragmatic, not unique","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:18:{"id":"sae-probing-2502.16681","title":"Are Sparse Autoencoders Useful? A Case Study in Sparse Probing","venue":"arXiv","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2502.16681","claim":"Across data-scarce, class-imbalanced, label-noise, and distribution-shift probing regimes, SAE probes occasionally beat baselines on individual datasets but no SAE(+ensemble) method consistently beats standard baselines","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:20:{"id":"gdm-sae-negative-2025","title":"Negative Results for SAEs On Downstream Tasks and Deprioritising SAE Research (GDM mech-interp team)","venue":"Alignment Forum (Google DeepMind team post)","year":2025,"url":"https://www.alignmentforum.org/posts/4uXCAJNuPKtKBsi28/sae-progress-update-negative-results-for-saes-on-downstream","claim":"2025-03-26: dense linear probes vastly outperform SAE probes incl. OOD harmful-intent detection; chat-data SAE finetuning closes only ~half the gap; GDM deprioritises fundamental SAE research (not 'SAEs are useless'); SAEs still useful for dataset debugging/spurious-correlation discovery","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:24:{"id":"capacity-2404.05405","title":"Physics of Language Models Part 3.3: Knowledge Capacity Scaling Laws","venue":"arXiv (Meta/MBZUAI); ICML 2025 status not confirmed at source","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2404.05405","claim":"LMs store max ~2 bits of factual knowledge per parameter (bit-complexity of stored tuples, controlled synthetic corpora), stable to int8 quantisation; GPT-2-with-RoPE matches/exceeds LLaMA/Mistral architectures at knowledge storage; MoE sparsity, insufficient exposure, and junk data reduce capacity; domain-name prepending increases it. USE LIMIT: a synthetic-conditions capacity estimate — NOT an upper bound on external-store bytes needed to backfill a parameter cut (a store additionally pays addressing/keys/schema/retrieval-index overhead)","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:26:{"id":"memory-layers-2412.09764","title":"Memory Layers at Scale","venue":"arXiv (Meta)","year":2024,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2412.09764","claim":"Trainable sparse key-value memory layers replacing FFN capacity: beat dense models given >2x the compute and MoE at matched resources, largest gains on factual tasks; scaled to 128B memory parameters over 1T training tokens — factual capacity is separable from dense compute and relocatable into a lookup structure","verified":true}
docs/next/lit/SURG.sources.jsonl:30:{"id":"sspu-2505.24428","title":"Model Unlearning via Sparse Autoencoder Subspace Guided Projections (SSPU)","venue":"arXiv","year":2025,"url":"https://arxiv.org/abs/2505.24428","claim":"SAE-guided layer/feature selection + QR subspace construction + constrained optimisation steering activations into an 'irrelevant' subspace; -3.22% harmful-knowledge accuracy vs strongest baseline on WMDP-Cyber with utility retained; REMOVAL ONLY — no external-store backfill, no parameter deletion","verified":true}
