docs/next/lit/STORE.sources.jsonl:2:{"id": "hirschman-crowdsourcing-curation-2016", "title": "Crowdsourcing and curation: perspectives from biology and natural language processing", "author": "Hirschman L, Fort K, Boué S, Kyrpides N, Islamaj Doğan R, Cohen KB", "venue": "Database (Oxford)", "year": 2016, "url": "https://academic.oup.com/database/article/doi/10.1093/database/baw115/2630501", "doi": "10.1093/database/baw115", "claim": "Perspectives/review paper on crowdsourcing in biocuration (micro-tasking, community editing, GWAP), examining expertise needed, participant motivation, feasibility, cost and quality. As summarised in this paper: a crowdsourced drug-indication experiment reached ~$1.75/abstract for five independent judgements each and ~96% precision / ~89% recall; a separate gene-mutation crowd experiment reached ~80% precision / >70% recall for <$1/abstract; the cited EXPERT-curator baseline was ~90% precision / ~70% recall. Manual curation baseline: 15-20 min/abstract at $30/curator-hour ($2.75-$10/paper). Lesson: crowd curation with redundancy can reach expert-competitive quality on some extraction tasks at low unit cost, but recall/precision vary by task and redundancy multiplies unit cost.", "verified": true, "verification": "REVISION 2026-07-11b: authors CORRECTED (prior draft wrongly attributed this DOI to 'Good BM, Su AI'). OUP full text fetched 2026-07-11; author list, cost/quality figures, and the crowd-vs-expert attribution extracted. The $1.75 drug-indication figure originates in Good et al. 2015 (bav016, separate source) and is here restated as summarised by Hirschman et al."}
